This proposes adding the following public API to `IMethodSymbol`:

```cs
/// <summary>
/// Indicates whether the method is declared readonly, i.e.
/// whether 'this' is readonly in the scope of the method.
/// See also <see cref="IsEffectivelyReadOnly"/>
/// </summary>
bool IsDeclaredReadOnly { get; }

/// <summary>
/// Indicates whether the method is effectively readonly,
/// by either the method or the containing type being marked readonly.
/// </summary>
bool IsEffectivelyReadOnly { get; }
```

Note that once the last prototype comments are addressed, the check `methodSymbol.IsEffectivelyReadOnly` will be basically equivalent to `methodSymbol.ThisParameter.RefKind == RefKind.In`.

**Version Used**: Visual Studio Proffesional 2019 Preview 16.0.0 Preview 4.4



**Steps to Reproduce**:

```C#
interface I
{
    void Foo<T>(T value);
    void Foo<T>(T? value) where T : struct;
}

//works fine
class C1 : I
{
    public void Foo<T>(T value) { }
    public void Foo<T>(T? value) where T : struct { }
}

//several build errors
class C2 : I
{
    void I.Foo<T>(T value) { }

    //error CS0111: Type 'C2' already defines a member called 'I.Foo' with the same parameter types
    void I.Foo<T>(T? value) { }
}
```

Reproducible also in sharplab:
https://sharplab.io/#v2:

**Expected Behavior**: Compiles fine as in previous version (VS 2017).

**Actual Behavior**: Does not compile.
